“Introducing ‘TempusFlora’: A personalized biodome ecosystem that visually and sonically chronicles the decomposition of a chosen organic material – a fallen leaf, a discarded apple core, even a lock of hair! Inside, miniature, bio-robotic ‘BloomBots’ – tiny, insect-like machines – collect spectral data, analyze microbial activity via embedded sensors, and translate this data into a constantly shifting, bioluminescent bloom of color and light. The intensity, hue, and patterns of the bloom dynamically reflect the decay process – a slow, melancholic blue for cellulose breakdown, a vibrant orange for bacterial action, a pulsing violet hinting at fungal growth. Users can ‘tune’ the BloomBots’ sensitivity, creating variations in bloom intensity and complexity. The device includes a haptic feedback layer – a delicate, textured surface that subtly shifts in temperature and pressure mirroring the decaying matter’s core temperature. Furthermore, a subtle ultrasonic soundscape – generated by the BloomBots themselves – corresponds to the bloom’s visual evolution, adding another layer of sensory information. Users can document the entire bloom's lifecycle via a companion app, creating a stunning, interactive ‘temporal portrait’ of their chosen decay. The ultimate aim? To turn the inevitably sad process of decomposition into an exquisite, meditative, and scientifically-rich experience.”